In this edition (BSB-Ink. S-25; IBP 4859), line 1 of this leaf reads: "da fuga pleri[que] abiectis armis proximu[m] collem occupauere : nox at[que] preda". In another edition (GW M39666; VD 16 S 1397), this line reads: "seda fuga pleri[que] abiectis armis [pro]ximu[m] collem occupauere : nox at[que] p[re]da". (Goff S-88, giving an imprint consistent with the latter edition, appears to conflate the two.) Established heading: Sallust, 86-34 B.C. Established heading: Landsberg, Martin, d. 1523 Penn Libraries call number: Inc S-88 All images from this book

photo.title: Bookplate of James Carson Brevoort (1818-1887)
photo.description: Bookplate of James Carson Brevoort (1818-1887), American bibliophile, antiquarian and natural historian. He was a collector of rare books and coins. From his father, Henry Brevoort, he inherited about 6,000 volumes, mostly Americana, which were collected in Europe during the turbulent years from 1810 until 1832. To this library, Brevoort made large additions, until in 1875 it comprised about 10,000 volumes, many of them very rare and costly. He also collected medals and manuscripts. About 1875 he began to bestow many of his treasures upon various institutions. His collections also embraced entomology and ichthyology (books and specimens). Established heading: Brevoort, James Carson, 1818-1887 Penn Libraries call number: EC6 M6427 645pb All images from this book

photo.title: Metal-cut printer's device of Guy Marchant of Paris
photo.description: Metal-cut printer's device of Guy Marchant of Paris: "[T]he third of Guy Marchant's six devices ... At the top is a rebus consisting of musical notes, sol and la and the words Fides ficit, to represent the motto, 'Sola fides sufficit' (from the hymn, 'Pange lingua gloriosi,' of St. Thomas Aquinas). Below the motto are the initials, G and M, the G being set in type and the M cut in the block. Below these are two clasped hands issuing from clouds and flanked by angels. The device depicts the workshop of Saints Crispin and Crispinian, patron saints of shoemakers. It has been suggested that the presence of these saints might be explained if Marchant were a native of Soissons, where they were especially honored. Between the saints is a shield, with a book, possibly a Bible, held open by two hands. The word, sola (sole of the foot) and the boots in the shoeshop suggest the word marchant, a play on the printer's name." --M. Harman, Printer's and publisher's devices in incunabula in the University of Illinois Library, no. 23. Established heading: Marchant, Guy Penn Libraries call number: Inc D-203 All images from this book

photo.title: Bookplate of Samuel Weiller Fernberger (1887-1956)
photo.description: Bookplate of Samuel Weiller Fernberger (1887-1956) Samuel Weiller Fernberger (1887-1956) received his Ph.D. in psychology from the University of Pennsylvania in 1912 and was a member of the faculty at Clark University from 1912 until his death. F. W. Irwin wrote in Fernberger's obituary in The American Journal of Psychology, Vol. 69.4 (1956), p. 677-678: "At all stages of his career he exhibited an interest in those applications of experimental psychology that employed rigorous, preferably psychophysical, methods. He once testified before the Public Service Commission of Pennsylvania as an expert for the complainant in an action brought by the Yellow Cab Company of Philadelphia to prevent the use by others of taxicabs with colors alleged to resemble too closely the color of Yellow Cabs. His testimony involved not only verbal opinions but also the performance of demonstrations in the hearing room in the presence of the examiner and the interested parties. He mixed colors on a rotary color mixer to match the colors of the complainant's and respondent's cabs, showed that they were closely similar -- they differed by not more than three just noticeable differences along the base of a model of the color solid that was also produced -- and that their resemblance increased as the illumination of the room was decreased." Shortly before his death Fernberger donated a collection of psychological books and journals to the University of Pennsylvania as the Samuel W. Fernberger Collection of Psychology. Established heading: Fernberger, Samuel Weiller, 1887-1956 Other examples of Samuel Weiller Fernberger provenance Penn Libraries call number: EC6 F8484 630o

photo.title: Bookplate of Edmund McClure (d. 1922)
photo.description: Bookplate of Edmund McClure (d. 1922). He was editorial secretary of the Society for Promoting Christian Knowledge (SPCK) from 1875-1915. According to his obituary in The Times of London (20 November 1922; p. 5; issue 43193, col. B), "Throughout that long period he exercised a firm control over the great mass of publications issued by the society, and when he retired remarkable tributes were paid by leading churchmen to his zeal and ability." He also wrote several books on historical and religious topics. The phrase "Beatos puto quibus deorum munere datum est aut facere scribenda aut scribere legenda beatissimos vero quib[us] utru[m]que" comes from Pliny the Younger, epistle 6.16. Established heading: McClure, Edmund, -1922 Penn Libraries call number: Inc B-143 Folio All images from this book

tag.raw: De Trafford, Humphrey F. (Humphrey Francis), Sir, 1862-1929

photo.description: Armorial bookplate of Sir Humphrey Francis de Trafford, 3rd Baronet (1862-1929). According to his obituary in The Times of London (11 January 1929; p. 14, issue 45098, col. C), he was "a great sportsman, taking an active part in hunting, shooting, polo, cricket, lawn tennis, and coursing, while he was not less interested in field trials for sporting dogs, agricultural and dog shows, and the breeding of horses, cattle, dogs and other animals." Though he inherited great wealth on his father's death in 1886, by the 1890s he had fallen into considerable debt and sold the family estate, Trafford Park, in 1896. In 1904 a special Act of Parliament was passed "to relieve him of his embarrassments" (op. cit.), but in 1907 he again faced bankruptcy. According to a contemporary account in The New York Times (28 July 1907: C1.), "When asked how he came to get through such a vast sum as $2,500,000 in eighteen years, Sir Humphrey admitted that he had lost large amounts in betting and had to have recourse to money lenders, to one of whom he paid 15 per cent. interest." Established heading: De Trafford, Humphrey F. (Humphrey Francis), Sir, 1862-1929 Penn Libraries call number: Inc B-143 Folio All images from this book

photo.description: Ownership inscription of Anna Sophia Dormer (d. 1695) above an engraving of King Charles I of England (1600-1649). Anna Sophia Dormer was the daughter of Philip Herbert, 4th Earl of Pembroke and Lady Susan de Vere. She married Robert Dormer, 1st Earl of Carnarvon, an ardent royalist and supporter of Charles I. Text from the blessing of pilgrims, specifically their staves and purses. Mentioned as options in the blessing are the Virgin Mary as venerated in Aachen, St. Wolfgang (of Regensburg?) and the holy blood of "Welcze{...}", possibly Wilsnack, which argues for a German publication, possibly of the early 16th century, since the relics at Wilsnack were destroyed by Protestant reformers in 1558. Cf. this 1580 Ritus Ecclesiae Augustensis Episcopatus, which contains similar texts.] Penn Libraries call number: EC6 C2533 639i All images from this book
